In order to make your code cleaner, avoid `document.write()` and also not trigger redrawing every time you append an element to the DOM, you can put your markup into a variable and then set the `innerHTML` of the body (or any other element you want the list being output to), resulting in only one page redraw.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    var markup = &#39;&#39;;

    for (i = 0; i &lt;= 255; i++) {
      markup += i + &quot;: &quot; + i.toString(2) + &quot;&lt;br&gt;&quot;;
    }

    document.body.innerHTML = markup;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

The alternative to string concatenation is using a [document fragment](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/DocumentFragment):

&gt; ...because the document fragment isn&#39;t part of the active document tree structure, changes made to the fragment don&#39;t affect the document, cause reflow, or incur any performance impact that can occur when changes are made.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const fragment = document.createDocumentFragment();

    for (let i = 0; i &lt;= 255; i++) {
      const para = document.createElement(&#39;p&#39;);
      para.textContent = i + &quot;: &quot; + i.toString(2);
      fragment.appendChild(para);
    }

    document.body.appendChild(fragment);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

